docs.abstract: Both Musk, who once backed OpenAI, and Facebook’s parent company are set to unveil new services aimed at getting a piece of the artificial intelligence boom.
docs.snippet: Both Musk, who once backed OpenAI, and Facebook’s parent company are set to unveil new services aimed at getting a piece of the artificial intelligence boom.
docs.lead_paragraph: The rivalry between Mark Zuckerberg and Elon Musk won’t be confined to social media posts or a cage fight. The tech heavyweights are accelerating pushes into the artificial intelligence world to take on the Microsoft-backed OpenAI and Google, taking different approaches in the buzziest sector of the software industry.

headline.main: The A.I. Wars Heat Up as Elon Musk and Meta Enter the Ring

docs.abstract: Leading A.I. firms, including Microsoft, Google and OpenAI, will agree to voluntary guidelines that may be a first step to wider regulations.
docs.snippet: Leading A.I. firms, including Microsoft, Google and OpenAI, will agree to voluntary guidelines that may be a first step to wider regulations.
docs.lead_paragraph: In a potentially significant victory for the Biden administration, top players in artificial intelligence, including Microsoft, Google and OpenAI, are to meet at the White House on Friday to pledge to build safeguards into their development of a technology that has captivated Wall Street and rattled many world leaders.

headline.main: The White House Pushes Tech Leaders To Get Tough on A.I. Safety

docs.abstract: A new generation of chatbots doesn’t have many of the guardrails put in place by companies like Google and OpenAI, presenting new possibilities — and risks.
docs.snippet: A new generation of chatbots doesn’t have many of the guardrails put in place by companies like Google and OpenAI, presenting new possibilities — and risks.
docs.lead_paragraph: A.I. chatbots have lied about notable figures, pushed partisan messages, spewed misinformation or even advised users on how to commit suicide.

headline.main: Uncensored Chatbots Provoke a Fracas Over Free Speech
headline.print_headline: Chatbots Without Guardrails Open Next Round of A.I. Debate

docs.abstract: The senators have forged a bipartisan alliance to create a new federal agency to police the power of tech giants like Amazon, Apple and Meta.
docs.snippet: The senators have forged a bipartisan alliance to create a new federal agency to police the power of tech giants like Amazon, Apple and Meta.
docs.lead_paragraph: For years, policymakers have worried about the growing power of digital giants like Alphabet, Amazon, Apple, Meta and Microsoft, as they came to dominate more and more of everyday life. Now, two prominent senators are pushing to create a new federal agency to rein in the power of Big Tech.

headline.main: Warren and Graham Team Up to Take on Big Tech

docs.abstract: Amazon, Google and Meta are among the companies that announced the guidelines as they race to outdo each other with versions of artificial intelligence.
docs.snippet: Amazon, Google and Meta are among the companies that announced the guidelines as they race to outdo each other with versions of artificial intelligence.
docs.lead_paragraph: Seven leading A.I. companies in the United States have agreed to voluntary safeguards on the technology’s development, the White House announced on Friday, pledging to manage the risks of the new tools even as they compete over the potential of artificial intelligence.

headline.main: Pressured by Biden, A.I. Companies Agree to Guardrails on New Tools
headline.print_headline: Pressed by Biden, Big Tech Agrees to A.I. Rules

byline.original: By Michael D. Shear, Cecilia Kang and David E. Sanger

docs.abstract: While there has been a flurry of activity by the White House and lawmakers over artificial intelligence, rules for the technology remain distant, lawmakers and experts said.
docs.snippet: While there has been a flurry of activity by the White House and lawmakers over artificial intelligence, rules for the technology remain distant, lawmakers and experts said.
docs.lead_paragraph: Regulating artificial intelligence has been a hot topic in Washington in recent months, with lawmakers holding hearings and news conferences and the White House announcing voluntary A.I. safety commitments by seven technology companies on Friday.

headline.main: In U.S., Regulating A.I. Is in Its ‘Early Days’
headline.print_headline: Lots of Disagreement on How to Regulate Fast-Changing Technology

docs.abstract: The U.S. government is struggling to crack down on corporate concentration.
docs.snippet: The U.S. government is struggling to crack down on corporate concentration.
docs.lead_paragraph: When President Biden took office, he sent several signals that he was ready to take on increasing corporate concentration. Among the clearest was appointing the consumer advocate Lina Khan — a prominent critic of monopoly power — to lead the Federal Trade Commission.

headline.print_headline: With Federal Reins Loose, Big Business Gets Bigger
